 Job Description of a Product Manager in Financial Services | Chron.com              Skip to main content.  Job Description of a Product Manager in Financial Services  by Harlow Keith        A product manager will often pitch new products or services to potential investors. Keith Brofsky/Photodisc/Getty Images   Related Articles  1 [Financial Services Sector] | Interviewing Tips for the Financial Services Sector 2 [Financial Services Sales] | Job Description of a Financial Services Sales Representative 3 [Credit Manager] | The Role of a Credit Manager in a Bank 4 [Financial Services] | Pros & Cons of a Career in Financial Services    A product manager working in the financial services industry is in charge of developing a strategy to sell a product. This involves planning and assisting in the development, marketing and distribution of a product. Product managers also have to provide a clear plan for their product, outlining goals as well as potential risks, challenges and opportunities. They play a very active role within a company, leading and motivating teams to achieve their desired outcomes.        Educational Requirements Product managers who work in the financial services industry have at least a bachelor’s degree in finance, marketing, business management or another related field of study. Many individuals have a master’s degree in business administration, however. This position requires an extensive knowledge of finance and marketing, so you'll need a strong background in both fields. Many product managers in the financial services industry possess skills in accounting to help them balance budgets. Skills and Experience In order to be a product manager in financial services, you'll need at least five years of experience in a finance or management role, although most employers prefer more. Moreover, you'll need strong teamwork skills and the ability to inspire your fellow team members. Project managers have the necessary time and project management skills in order to complete their projects in a timely manner. Finally, you'll need to be able to use spreadsheets to analyze financial data and predict future costs, revenues and profits. Primary Responsibilities The principal duty of a product manager in financial services is to develop a strategy from inception to completion of a product. You'll have to work with the design and engineering teams to develop the product, the marketing team to effectively market the product and outside vendors to distribute and sell your product. Along the way, you'll have to complete financial analysis to model the product’s cost and potential margin. In addition, you'll be in charge of driving different teams and departments to make sure you achieve all of your initial goals. Additional Duties While developing your product, you'll also have to present your strategy to partners and shareholders. You'll outline how you plan to achieve your objective and lay out the potential risks and opportunities. Product managers in financial services regularly meet with clients about their interests. Furthermore, you may have to pitch your product to third-party vendors. All of these responsibilities will require strong communication skills. You may have to travel often in order to meet with customers and potential clients.              References (2)   KForce: Financial Services Project ManagerBirch Communications: Senior Product Manager   About the Author Harlow Keith has been involved in the human resources sector since 1998. He founded a human resources training company and has written several published articles. Harlow became interested in his field at the tender age of 15 while editing his father's resume.    Photo Credits  Keith Brofsky/Photodisc/Getty Images    Suggest an Article Correction      Related Searches           More Articles    [Product Marketing Consultant] | Job Description for a Product Marketing Consultant    [Product Analyst] | Product Analyst Duties    [Banking Relationship Manager] | Job Description for a Commercial Banking Relationship Manager    [Financial Reporting Manager] | The Job Description of a Financial Reporting Manager          Also Viewed  [Marketing Manager] | How Much Does a Marketing Manager Get Paid? [Product Management] | Product Management Cover Letter [Product Specialist] | Product Specialist Pay Scale [Brand Champion] | Responsibilities & Duties of a Brand Champion [Tips] | Tips For Being a Good Demonstrator [Pay Scale] | Pay Scale for a Marketing Coordinator [Accounts Receivable] | The Manager's Responsibilities for Accounts Receivable            












